<!--
	Guided Lecture Notes worksheet: "Linear Systems"
	Book sections (Exploring Differential Equations, geoff-cox/debookrs):
		c13-linsys/sec-introduction-to-systems.ptx
		c13-linsys/sec-variable-interactions.ptx
		c13-linsys/sec-linear-systems.ptx
		c13-linsys/sec-second-order-to-system.ptx
		c13-linsys/sec-solving-linear-systems.ptx
		c13-linsys/sec-qualitative-methods-systems.ptx
	Old deck: source/notes/latex/ folder "09 systems-reduction-of-order".
	Previous worksheet: ws-piecewise-forcing.ptx; next: ws-nonlinear-systems.

	Per the sourcing rules, every worked instance here is fresh: no
	example system, conversion, or solve appears in the book, the old
	deck, or earlier worksheets. Per the instructor overrides in
	CLAUDE.md section 4: no interactive content (phase-plane work is
	described qualitatively in text; no plotting tools), and the whole
	topic stays on this one worksheet.

	Worksheet conventions: checklists/worksheet-conventions.md (see
	CLAUDE.md section 4 for this repo's parameters). In brief:
	  * Student/instructor split via component="stu" / component="key",
	    mirrored in structure; answers never live inside <fillin>.
	  * Worked problems: paired <exercise component="stu" workspace="Xin">
	    and <exercise component="key"> (statement + solution).
	  * True/False checks: one <exercise> + <solution component="key">.
	  * <page> = vertical print space, not topics; headings are
	    <p><term>...</term></p>; display math uses <md> (<me>/<men> are
	    prohibited here).
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-linear-systems" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Linear Systems</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li><p><term>Recognize</term> systems of differential equations, and classify them as coupled or uncoupled, linear or nonlinear.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Convert</term> a second-order equation into a first-order system with the substitution <m>v = y'</m>.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Solve</term> a coupled linear system by guessing exponential solutions and finding the special rates <m>r</m>.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Interpret</term> the signs of the rates: which directions attract, which repel, and where trajectories go long-term.</p></li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 1 : What systems are; coupled vs uncoupled, linear vs not       -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Two unknowns, one story.</term></p>

		<p>
			So far every model tracked one quantity. Real situations rarely
			cooperate: predators and prey, two connected tanks, position and
			velocity&#8212;each changes at a rate that depends on the
			<em>others</em>. A <term>system</term> of differential equations
			tracks several unknown functions at once. When each equation involves
			only its own unknown, the system is <term>uncoupled</term> and the
			equations can be solved separately; when the unknowns appear in each
			other's equations, the system is <term>coupled</term> and must be
			solved together.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						A system is <fillin characters="9"/> when the unknowns appear in
						each other's equations; it is linear when each equation is a sum
						of the unknowns times <fillin characters="12"/>, with no products
						or compositions of the unknowns.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						A system is <m>\underline{\textbf{coupled}}</m> when the unknowns
						appear in each other's equations; it is linear when each equation
						is a sum of the unknowns times
						<m>\underline{\textbf{coefficients}}</m>, with no products or
						compositions of the unknowns.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-ex-classify" component="stu" workspace="2.4in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Classify each system: coupled or uncoupled, and linear or
					nonlinear.
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ \begin{cases} x' = 3x \\ y' = -4y \end{cases} \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ \begin{cases} x' = x - 2y \\ y' = 3x + y \end{cases} \qquad
						       \text{(c)}\ \begin{cases} x' = y^2 \\ y' = x \end{cases} </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-ex-classify" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Classify each system: coupled or uncoupled, and linear or
					nonlinear.
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ \begin{cases} x' = 3x \\ y' = -4y \end{cases} \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ \begin{cases} x' = x - 2y \\ y' = 3x + y \end{cases} \qquad
						       \text{(c)}\ \begin{cases} x' = y^2 \\ y' = x \end{cases} </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Uncoupled and linear: each equation mentions only its own
					unknown, so this is really two separate one-variable problems
					wearing a system costume (<m>x = c_1 e^{3t}</m>,
					<m>y = c_2 e^{-4t}</m>).
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Coupled and linear: <m>y</m> appears in the <m>x'</m> equation
					and <m>x</m> in the <m>y'</m> equation, but only through constant
					multiples.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) Coupled and <em>nonlinear</em>: the <m>y^2</m> disqualifies
					linearity even though everything is coupled politely.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-tf-uncoupled">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>An uncoupled system requires new solution techniques beyond this course's one-equation methods.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False. Uncoupled equations ignore each other, so each is solved
					alone with the usual first-order tools. Coupling is the whole
					difficulty&#8212;and the reason this chapter exists.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 2 : Second-order equations as systems                            -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Old friends in new clothes: second order as a system.</term></p>

		<p>
			Systems are not just for multi-quantity models: <em>any</em>
			second-order equation can be rewritten as a first-order system by
			naming the derivative. Set <m>v = y'</m>; then <m>v' = y''</m>, and
			one second-order equation becomes two first-order ones. This is how
			software solves higher-order equations&#8212;and it ties this chapter
			to everything since c8.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						To convert <m>y'' = F(y, y')</m> into a system, introduce the new
						unknown <m>v = </m><fillin characters="3"/>; the first equation of
						the system is then <m>y' = v</m>, and the second is
						<m>v' = </m><fillin characters="8"/>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						To convert <m>y'' = F(y, y')</m> into a system, introduce the new
						unknown <m>v = \underline{\textbf{y'}}</m>; the first equation of
						the system is then <m>y' = v</m>, and the second is
						<m>v' = \underline{\textbf{F(y,v)}}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-ex-convert" component="stu" workspace="2.4in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Convert the second-order equation
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' + 5y' + 4y = 0 </mrow>
					</md>
					into a first-order system in the unknowns <m>y</m> and
					<m>v = y'</m>. Is the resulting system coupled? Linear?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-ex-convert" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Convert the second-order equation
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' + 5y' + 4y = 0 </mrow>
					</md>
					into a first-order system in the unknowns <m>y</m> and
					<m>v = y'</m>. Is the resulting system coupled? Linear?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					With <m>v = y'</m>, we have <m>v' = y'' = -4y - 5v</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> \begin{cases} y' = v \\ v' = -4y - 5v \end{cases} </mrow>
					</md>
					The system is coupled (each equation uses the other unknown) and
					linear (constant coefficients, no products). Its exponential rates
					turn out to be exactly the characteristic roots of the original
					equation (<m>r = -1, -4</m>)&#8212;the two viewpoints carry the
					same information.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-tf-order">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>A single third-order equation can be rewritten as a system of three first-order equations.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					True: name each derivative&#8212;<m>v = y'</m>,
					<m>w = y''</m>&#8212;and the third-order equation becomes three
					first-order equations in <m>y, v, w</m>. Order trades for
					dimension, one derivative per new unknown.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 3 : Solving a coupled system with exponential guesses            -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Solving by exponential guess.</term></p>

		<p>
			The LHCC insight survives the jump to systems: guess that
			<em>both</em> unknowns are multiples of the same exponential,
			<md>
				<mrow> x = a\,e^{rt}, \qquad y = b\,e^{rt}, </mrow>
			</md>
			substitute, cancel <m>e^{rt}</m>, and hunt for the special rates
			<m>r</m> (and direction pairs <m>(a,b)</m>) that make both equations
			hold with <m>a, b</m> not both zero.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						After substituting and canceling <m>e^{rt}</m>, the system
						becomes algebraic conditions on <m>r</m>, <m>a</m>, and
						<m>b</m>; a <m>2\times 2</m> linear system typically has
						<fillin characters="3"/> special rates, and each contributes one
						exponential building block to the <fillin characters="7"/>
						solution.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						After substituting and canceling <m>e^{rt}</m>, the system
						becomes algebraic conditions on <m>r</m>, <m>a</m>, and
						<m>b</m>; a <m>2\times 2</m> linear system typically has
						<m>\underline{\textbf{two}}</m> special rates, and each
						contributes one exponential building block to the
						<m>\underline{\textbf{general}}</m> solution.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-ex-solve" component="stu" workspace="3.6in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the coupled system
					<md>
						<mrow> \begin{cases} x' = x + 3y \\ y' = 3x + y \end{cases} </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Substitute <m>x = a e^{rt}</m>, <m>y = b e^{rt}</m> and cancel
					<m>e^{rt}</m>.
					(b) Show the two conditions force <m>r = 4</m> (with
					<m>b = a</m>) or <m>r = -2</m> (with <m>b = -a</m>).
					(c) Write the general solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-ex-solve" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the coupled system
					<md>
						<mrow> \begin{cases} x' = x + 3y \\ y' = 3x + y \end{cases} </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Substitute <m>x = a e^{rt}</m>, <m>y = b e^{rt}</m> and cancel
					<m>e^{rt}</m>.
					(b) Show the two conditions force <m>r = 4</m> (with
					<m>b = a</m>) or <m>r = -2</m> (with <m>b = -a</m>).
					(c) Write the general solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Since <m>x' = ra\,e^{rt}</m> and <m>y' = rb\,e^{rt}</m>,
					canceling <m>e^{rt}</m> leaves
					<md>
						<mrow> ra = a + 3b, \qquad rb = 3a + b. </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Adding the two conditions: <m>r(a+b) = 4(a+b)</m>; subtracting:
					<m>r(a-b) = -2(a-b)</m>. If <m>a + b \neq 0</m>, the first forces
					<m>r = 4</m>, and then the conditions give <m>b = a</m>. If
					<m>a - b \neq 0</m>, the second forces <m>r = -2</m> and
					<m>b = -a</m>. Two rates, each with its own direction:
					<m>r = 4</m> along <m>(1,1)</m>, and <m>r = -2</m> along
					<m>(1,-1)</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) Superposition assembles the general solution:
					<md>
						<mrow> x(t) \amp = c_1 e^{4t} + c_2 e^{-2t}, </mrow>
						<mrow> y(t) \amp = c_1 e^{4t} - c_2 e^{-2t}. </mrow>
					</md>
					Each building block is a <em>straight-line solution</em>: a
					trajectory that runs along its direction vector, growing or
					decaying at its rate.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 4 : Reading the rates; qualitative behavior                      -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Reading the rates: the phase-plane story.</term></p>

		<p>
			Plotting <m>(x(t), y(t))</m> as a moving point in the plane&#8212;the
			<term>phase plane</term>&#8212;turns the algebra into geometry.
			Straight-line solutions are the skeleton: directions with negative
			rates pull trajectories in, directions with positive rates push them
			out, and every other trajectory bends between the two.
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-ex-behavior" component="stu" workspace="2.8in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For the system solved on the previous page (rates <m>r = 4</m>
					along <m>(1,1)</m> and <m>r = -2</m> along <m>(1,-1)</m>):
					(a) Describe what happens to a solution that starts exactly on the
					line <m>y = -x</m>.
					(b) Describe the long-term behavior of a generic solution (both
					<m>c_1, c_2 \neq 0</m>).
					(c) Is the origin stable or unstable for this system?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-ex-behavior" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For the system solved on the previous page (rates <m>r = 4</m>
					along <m>(1,1)</m> and <m>r = -2</m> along <m>(1,-1)</m>):
					(a) Describe what happens to a solution that starts exactly on the
					line <m>y = -x</m>.
					(b) Describe the long-term behavior of a generic solution (both
					<m>c_1, c_2 \neq 0</m>).
					(c) Is the origin stable or unstable for this system?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Starting on <m>y = -x</m> means <m>c_1 = 0</m>: the solution is
					pure <m>e^{-2t}</m> along <m>(1,-1)</m>, so it slides straight into
					the origin and stays on that line forever.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) For a generic start, the <m>e^{-2t}</m> part dies while the
					<m>e^{4t}</m> part explodes, so the trajectory bends away and
					eventually runs off nearly parallel to the <m>(1,1)</m>
					direction. Trajectories approach along one line and flee along the
					other.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) Unstable&#8212;this mixed sign pattern (one negative rate, one
					positive) is called a <em>saddle</em>: almost every solution
					escapes, and only the knife-edge starts on <m>y = -x</m> are drawn
					in. The one-variable phase line from c6 has grown into a phase
					plane, but the vocabulary&#8212;attract, repel,
					stability&#8212;carries straight over.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ls-tf-decay">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>If both special rates of a <m>2\times 2</m> linear system are negative, every solution tends to the origin as <m>t \to \infty</m>.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					True. Every solution is a combination of the two exponential
					building blocks, and both decay&#8212;so the whole combination
					does too. The origin is then a sink for the entire plane, the
					two-dimensional cousin of c6's stable equilibrium.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<title>Looking ahead</title>
			<p>
				Linear systems bend to the exponential guess, just as LHCC
				equations did. The final worksheet faces systems that
				don't&#8212;<em>nonlinear</em> systems like predator&#8211;prey&#8212;where
				we find equilibria, linearize nearby, and let this worksheet's
				machinery describe each neighborhood of the phase plane.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>
</worksheet>
